"/> Well, yes. Murder is intentional killing. With malice (intent to
cause harm). Doing something stupid is negligence. If your
negligence results in somebody getting killed, that's manslaughter (or
negligent homicide, depending on which state).

It's even possible that he wasn't negligent at all. Say he had a
small stroke the night before that affected his ability to drive
safely. He might not notice it as he got up in the morning, got
dressed, etc. Only when he (literally) ran into the farmer's market
did his inability to drive show up.

I knew somebody who had a stroke in his 30s (rare, but it happens).
He got up in the morning, shaved, got dressed, drove to work, sat down
at his desk and started to work. He thought he was fine until a
co-worker walked by and said &quot;hello&quot;. Then he discovered that he
couldn't talk. There was nothing else wrong with him, he had just
lost the area of his brain that tells the vocal chords to make speech
sounds.

He drafted a short document explaining his problem and printed several
copies. Handed one to his boss, propped one up on his desk. Drove to
the hospital(*) and handed a copy to the triage nurse.

He eventually recovered some ability to speak, but had another stroke
and died less than a year later.

So, yes, it's quite possible that this old man could have lost his
ability to drive and not known about it until he killed 8 people and
injured 45 more. Sometimes accidents just happen. It's very sad,
but it's part of life.

(*) This may not have been the wisest move - for all he knew the
stroke *could* have affected his ability to drive an unfamiliar route
even though he had driven to work without problems.

OTOH, it's possible he had a degenerative disease like Alzheimer's.
In that case, the negligence was on the part of those who allowed him
to continue driving. My father had Frontal Lobe Dementia (similar to
Alzheimers but the symptoms occur in a different order). His driving
habits were very safe, but he developed a tendency to get lost. A
couple of times he failed to complete a left turn and ended up on the
wrong side of the street (no crash, just had to turn around and go
back).

We took away his car keys, but one time he got mad at my mother over
something. While she was in another room he got her keys from her
purse and drove off somewhere. Parked the car, got out and started
walking. Eventually somebody found him and called her. We picked him
up, drove around, and eventually found the car.

We knew he shouldn't drive, even wrote to the DMV asking to have his
license revoked. The eventually did, about 8 months later. By that
time he and mother had moved to an assisted living facility. Even
then, Mother would let him drive the car up and down the parking
structure. She said &quot;not letting him drive would be taking his
manhood away&quot;. This was a combination of forgetfulness (she has some
memory loss, but not nearly as bad as his) and denial.

Luckily he never hurt anybody or damaged anything. If he had, we
would have been at least partly responsible. But it wouldn't have
been _his_ fault. People with Alzheimer's don't know that they are
losing their faculties, and won't believe you if you tell them.
