"/> Some people over 90 are good drivers. If their mental processes and
vision/hearing are unimpaired, there is no reason not to continue
driving. But some people lose the ability to drive safely at 70 or
younger. My father was about 77 when his mental deterioration made it
unsafe for him to drive. But my father-in-law was still driving the
day before he died at age 89. Not that he was a particularly great
driver -- his car had several minor dents in it -- but as far as we
can tell he was no worse at 89 than he had been at 30. And my
mother-in-law stopped driving at night in her 60s because she found
oncoming headlights seemed to draw her toward them. She stopped
driving at all at about 80 because of macular degeneration -- she
could no longer see well enough to drive. (And I was printing books
from The Gutenberg Project in 60-point type so she could read them --
that means a capital M is over 3/4&quot; wide.)
